	   <tr><td colspan=2>Several points of view are going to be discussed on this topic, since there are so many different ways to play a cleric.  I play a battle cleric and am post 50, so maybe some of my points will have some bearing.<br><br>1.  The cleric is NOT a melee class.  Don't let the plate armor fool you buddy, you're basically a caster class with a strong back.  You CAN melee in a pinch, but your 12-18 damage will not be much compared to the damage the melee class can, and do, hit for on a regular basis.  You have a wide assortment of spells at your disposal, learn when and where to use them.<br><br>2.  At level 10, wisdom has very little effect on the mana pool.  Until level 30 or so, all your magic gear should be in +mana, +health, +sta, and + str respectfully.  What wisdom DOES effect at the lower levels is how fast your int/wis based skills will increase (this includes caster skills and most trade skills.)<br><br>3. Strength is VERY important to a cleric.  You will be wearing full plate armor for most of your life, and if you don't have at LEAST 80 strength, be prepared to waste some of your magic slots on strength if you want to move.  (A full set of Bronze will weigh approx 75-80.)<br><br>4.  Post 30, a cleric will want his wisdom to be as close to 200 as possible.  There is where your mana pool starts to get REALLY affected by wisdom, and the more mana the better.  You get a pool adjustment after 200, however, so don't bother to go higher.<br><br>5.  Be advised of the rest of your bonuses.  At 75 agi you get an ac bonus, for example, and all these bonuses are important to survival at high levels.<br><br>Teucer<br>Templar<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
